WEBVTT

00:01.502 --> 00:03.837
<i>[Judith Hill's "Today Is"]</i>

00:03.837 --> 00:08.175
<i>Meredith: Oxygen is
the human body's fuel.</i>

00:08.175 --> 00:09.468
<i>[together]
♪ Today ♪</i>

00:09.468 --> 00:10.552
<i>Meredith:
It powers our brains,</i>

00:10.552 --> 00:12.596
<i>organs, and bodily tissues.</i>

00:12.596 --> 00:13.680
<i>♪ It's a light,
come and see it now ♪</i>

00:13.680 --> 00:15.641
<i>[together]
♪ Today, today is ♪</i>

00:15.641 --> 00:17.226
<i>Meredith:
Without a proper supply,</i>

00:17.226 --> 00:20.062
<i>our bodies can't function.</i>

00:20.062 --> 00:23.690
I haven't written mine yet,
but I will by Friday.

00:23.690 --> 00:24.816
Wait, you already wrote

00:24.816 --> 00:25.734
and memorized your vows,
didn't you?

00:25.734 --> 00:26.985
I'm excited too.

00:26.985 --> 00:28.445
I just need more hours
in a day,

00:28.445 --> 00:30.155
but I did book a car
to pick up your parents.

00:30.155 --> 00:31.490
- <i>Meredith: Our brains...</i>
- Okay.

00:31.490 --> 00:32.241
<i>Meredith:
Hearts, and kidneys...</i>

00:32.241 --> 00:33.951
See you soon.

00:33.951 --> 00:35.619
<i>Meredith: Can only tolerate
a lack of oxygen</i>

00:35.619 --> 00:38.413
<i>for a limited time before
their cells begin to die.</i>

00:38.413 --> 00:40.249
Wow, you really know
what you're doing.

00:40.249 --> 00:42.584
I have had seven sister's
worth of hand-me-downs.

00:42.584 --> 00:44.461
This is nothing.

00:44.461 --> 00:46.213
Wouldn't have pegged you
for a vintage dress though.

00:46.213 --> 00:48.257
- I was gonna rock a jumpsuit.
- Fierce!

00:48.257 --> 00:50.467
But then my grandma pulled
my mom's dress

00:50.467 --> 00:51.927
from the attic,
because she thinks I'm my mom.

00:51.927 --> 00:54.972
And it just felt like a sign.

00:54.972 --> 00:56.974
I'm just lucky
you have tailoring skills.

00:56.974 --> 00:59.518
Lucky, and also,
you're getting a bill.

00:59.518 --> 01:01.603
<i>Meredith: About five minutes
for the brain...</i>

01:01.603 --> 01:04.523
<i>- ♪ Come and feel it now ♪</i>
- Wow.

01:04.523 --> 01:05.732
<i>Meredith: About 30
for the heart and kidneys.</i>

01:05.732 --> 01:07.150
Don't look.

01:07.150 --> 01:08.277
It's bad luck for the bride
to see the roommate

01:08.277 --> 01:10.028
before the wedding.

01:10.028 --> 01:11.488
Yeah, you're fine.

01:11.488 --> 01:12.906
Have you guys seen
this email?

01:12.906 --> 01:14.449
Apparently, Dr. Webber has

01:14.449 --> 01:16.076
a special announcement
this morning.

01:16.076 --> 01:17.536
Wait, do you think
the residency program

01:17.536 --> 01:18.787
is coming off probation?

01:18.787 --> 01:20.205
Or maybe Grey or Pierce
is coming back?

01:20.205 --> 01:21.123
Or they're finally putting
cheese curls

01:21.123 --> 01:22.791
back in the vending machine.

01:22.791 --> 01:25.085
It's more likely
than either of yours.

01:25.085 --> 01:26.420
We're leaving in five minutes.

01:26.420 --> 01:28.380
I'm only gonna tell you once, okay?

01:28.380 --> 01:29.923
She's still
in a wedding dress.

01:29.923 --> 01:32.301
And you're slow.
Get in the shower.

01:32.301 --> 01:34.595
<i>♪ Your moment shining down ♪</i>

01:34.595 --> 01:36.430
<i>Meredith:
When a patient loses oxygen,</i>

01:36.430 --> 01:39.683
<i>doctors know the clock
is ticking.</i>

01:39.683 --> 01:41.476
<i>♪ It's a vibe,
can you feel it now? ♪</i>

01:44.271 --> 01:47.524
- Matcha latte, your favorite.
- Thanks.

01:47.524 --> 01:49.109
You could have one every day
if you came back.

01:49.109 --> 01:50.736
Could have one every day now.

01:50.736 --> 01:53.530
Well, yeah, but you wouldn't
need to cross the street.

01:53.530 --> 01:56.366
Plus, you could wear scrubs,
which are basically pajamas.

01:56.366 --> 01:58.535
Are those
your big selling points?

01:58.535 --> 02:00.787
Well, Webber has
an announcement this morning.

02:00.787 --> 02:02.289
That's gotta be good news.

02:02.289 --> 02:03.540
Yeah, well,
don't get your hopes up.

02:03.540 --> 02:05.292
I only agreed to talk
to a few people.

02:05.292 --> 02:07.502
- Ooh, I gotta go.
- Oh!

02:07.502 --> 02:09.171
You get to save lives...

02:09.171 --> 02:10.922
in pajamas!

02:10.922 --> 02:12.299
BokHee, hey.

02:12.299 --> 02:15.927
Um, uh, attention, everyone. Attention.

02:15.927 --> 02:18.472
We have some exciting news
that we want to share.

02:18.472 --> 02:21.183
As you know, each year,
the Catherine Fox Award

02:21.183 --> 02:23.310
recognizes surgical innovations

02:23.310 --> 02:25.854
that push the boundaries
of modern medicine.

02:25.854 --> 02:28.732
It's been some time since
Grey Sloan's had a nominee,

02:28.732 --> 02:31.526
but this morning,
we received word that not one

02:31.526 --> 02:35.030
but two of our doctors
have been nominated.

02:35.030 --> 02:37.783
Please join me
in congratulating

02:37.783 --> 02:39.660
Dr. Nick Marsh

02:39.660 --> 02:42.704
nominated for his work
on xenotransplantation.

02:42.704 --> 02:44.623
Wow, thank you.

02:44.623 --> 02:47.793
And Dr. Winston Ndugu,

02:47.793 --> 02:51.004
who's been nominated
along with Dr. Maggie Pierce

02:51.004 --> 02:53.548
for their groundbreaking
partial heart transplant.

02:53.548 --> 02:57.177
[applause]

02:57.177 --> 02:59.012
We look forward
to celebrating you

02:59.012 --> 03:00.847
at the award ceremony
in Boston.

03:00.847 --> 03:04.017
[applause]

03:04.017 --> 03:06.812
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

03:09.564 --> 03:12.317
Congratulations again
to both of you

03:12.317 --> 03:14.277
I've got seats
on the Fox Foundation jet.

03:14.277 --> 03:15.612
Thank you.

03:15.612 --> 03:17.739
I'm headed to the OR now,
but I'm truly honored.

03:17.739 --> 03:19.032
Congratulations.

03:23.995 --> 03:25.831
[sighs]

03:27.749 --> 03:29.876
I'll have information
about the ceremony

03:29.876 --> 03:31.420
and travel plans later today.

03:31.420 --> 03:33.713
We're just finalizing
a few things.

03:33.713 --> 03:34.881
That's okay.
I'm good.

03:34.881 --> 03:37.008
I'm--I'm not going.

03:38.218 --> 03:39.386
But thank you.

03:39.386 --> 03:41.680
Sam Sutton
post-op day two status.

03:41.680 --> 03:43.765
Post upper and lower limb
fracture repairs

03:43.765 --> 03:46.435
and right lower extremity
gastroc flap.

03:46.435 --> 03:49.855
All Doppler signals are strong,
and no sign of infection.

03:49.855 --> 03:51.481
I hear I'm gonna be famous.

03:51.481 --> 03:52.899
Well, it depends
on how you define it.

03:52.899 --> 03:53.984
We're writing up your case
for a medical journal,

03:53.984 --> 03:55.819
not "The New York Times."

03:55.819 --> 03:57.863
But we do hope it'll help
other doctors and patients.

03:57.863 --> 03:58.947
So they know how to treat

03:58.947 --> 04:00.699
the next guy
who breaks 93 bones.

04:00.699 --> 04:01.783
[all chuckle]

04:01.783 --> 04:03.160
Well, your vitals look good.

04:03.160 --> 04:04.744
I'll come back
and check on you later tonight.

04:04.744 --> 04:06.246
Great. What happened
to my other doctor?

04:06.246 --> 04:09.291
Uh, Dr. Griffith, the intern?

04:09.291 --> 04:11.084
No, no, no,
she had light brown hair,

04:11.084 --> 04:13.336
Disney princess eyes,
heart-stopping smile.

04:13.336 --> 04:14.921
- Dr. Wilson?
- Yes.

04:14.921 --> 04:16.256
Is Dr. Wilson single,

04:16.256 --> 04:17.883
or did she just say that
because I was dying?

04:17.883 --> 04:19.009
She said that?

04:20.218 --> 04:21.761
Well,
she's with other patients,

04:21.761 --> 04:23.722
but Dr. Yasuda
will be taking your data

04:23.722 --> 04:25.140
for the rest of the day,
so if you need something,

04:25.140 --> 04:27.267
- just ask her.
- All right.

04:27.267 --> 04:28.268
Yeah.

04:28.268 --> 04:29.895
<i>[light quirky music]</i>

04:29.895 --> 04:31.104
You can call me
a Disney princess,

04:31.104 --> 04:32.898
but I don't date patients.

04:32.898 --> 04:35.358
And we should also monitor
her urine output

04:35.358 --> 04:37.068
and fluid status.

04:37.068 --> 04:39.863
Uh, Dr. Bailey?

04:39.863 --> 04:41.323
May I please
be on your service?

04:41.323 --> 04:43.074
I thought
you were on Shepherd's.

04:43.074 --> 04:44.868
I was, but I know this case,

04:44.868 --> 04:47.078
and I can provide
a high level of care.

04:47.078 --> 04:49.289
You know the patient,

04:49.289 --> 04:51.875
which is a reason
for you not to be on the case.

04:51.875 --> 04:53.293
She and I are not family,

04:53.293 --> 04:54.753
and we've barely
known each other

04:54.753 --> 04:57.380
for more than a few months.
I can be professional.

04:57.380 --> 04:58.298
I'm happy to switch.

05:00.133 --> 05:02.761
Okay, Millin, you're with me.
Kwan, go find Shepherd.

05:04.930 --> 05:06.473
Hello.

05:06.473 --> 05:07.599
Hello, Doctor.

05:07.599 --> 05:09.559
Maxine Anderson,
81 years old.

05:09.559 --> 05:10.769
Diagnosed with a UTI

05:10.769 --> 05:12.854
complicated
by delirium and sepsis.

05:12.854 --> 05:14.940
Treated with IV antibiotics.

05:14.940 --> 05:16.233
Her delirium has resolved,

05:16.233 --> 05:18.360
and she's been off pressors
for 24 hours.

05:18.360 --> 05:20.987
She's being downgraded
to a stepdown bed today.

05:20.987 --> 05:23.824
- How are you feeling today?
- Much better, thank heavens.

05:23.824 --> 05:25.867
I lost my marbles there
for a minute.

05:25.867 --> 05:28.703
Well,
glad you're feeling better.

05:28.703 --> 05:31.414
Jules--I mean, Dr. Millin,

05:31.414 --> 05:33.083
if that happens again,

05:33.083 --> 05:35.085
I want you
to know a few things.

05:35.085 --> 05:38.213
First, please remember
to feed Mr. Darcy.

05:38.213 --> 05:39.923
The cat.

05:39.923 --> 05:41.216
Got it.
What else?

05:41.216 --> 05:42.759
I want to be cremated.

05:42.759 --> 05:45.011
Spread my ashes
in the Grand Canyon

05:45.011 --> 05:46.930
and play Tom Jones
at my funeral.

05:46.930 --> 05:47.931
Max--

05:47.931 --> 05:50.308
And if I'm going,

05:50.308 --> 05:51.810
just let me go.

05:51.810 --> 05:53.270
I do not want to lie around

05:53.270 --> 05:55.856
like a turnip
for the rest of my days.

05:55.856 --> 05:59.985
No shocking with paddles,
no tube down my throat.

05:59.985 --> 06:02.153
I want to be remembered
as a vibrant 81.

06:02.153 --> 06:03.655
Max, you're not dying.

06:03.655 --> 06:06.157
You're being moved from the ICU
to a regular room.

06:06.157 --> 06:09.327
But we understand
your wishes,

06:09.327 --> 06:11.329
and we'll get you
the paperwork.

06:11.329 --> 06:12.622
You'll be able to go home
in a day or two.

06:12.622 --> 06:15.917
Oh, that's great news,
not that I mind it here.

06:15.917 --> 06:17.794
The food's edible,

06:17.794 --> 06:20.213
the orderlies
are quite good-looking,

06:20.213 --> 06:22.841
and with Jules
sleeping down the hall,

06:22.841 --> 06:24.843
it almost feels like home.

06:24.843 --> 06:26.553
I've had a couple
of late nights.

06:26.553 --> 06:28.847
That's what the on-call room
is for, right?

06:28.847 --> 06:33.685
Okay, Mrs. Anderson,
Dr. Millin will transport you,

06:33.685 --> 06:36.521
and I will see you
in your new room.

06:36.521 --> 06:38.773
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:38.773 --> 06:42.068
- Max.
- Oh, I forgot.

06:42.068 --> 06:44.821
Either of you ever seen
an abdominal aortic aneurysm?

06:44.821 --> 06:46.072
Only in textbooks.

06:46.072 --> 06:47.449
I read that triple As
are super rare,

06:47.449 --> 06:49.075
Basically unheard of
in patients under 60.

06:49.075 --> 06:50.660
That's right.
Keep up, please.

06:50.660 --> 06:51.870
Well, our guy's only 29,

06:51.870 --> 06:53.121
and he's
a non-smoking vegetarian

06:53.121 --> 06:54.497
with no predisposing
genetic history

06:54.497 --> 06:55.957
of cardiac disease.

06:55.957 --> 06:57.792
What are the triple As
most serious complications?

06:57.792 --> 06:59.419
Dissection,
a tear in the aortic lining

06:59.419 --> 07:00.962
requires stenting or surgery.

07:00.962 --> 07:02.380
Rupture,
if the aneurysm bursts,

07:02.380 --> 07:04.007
we gotta take him
straight to the OR.

07:04.007 --> 07:05.342
- Good.
- Is that why we're rushing?

07:05.342 --> 07:06.384
Not exactly.

07:08.011 --> 07:10.138
No, no, no, no, no, not again.
Ray, listen.

07:10.138 --> 07:11.931
Look, I'm sorry,
Dr. Altman, okay?

07:11.931 --> 07:15.143
- I can't do this today.
- Ray.

07:15.143 --> 07:17.103
Sorry, sorry.
Excuse me, excuse me.

07:17.103 --> 07:18.563
Uh, what are we supposed
to do now?

07:18.563 --> 07:19.731
We run after him.

07:19.731 --> 07:22.484
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

07:22.484 --> 07:23.777
[sighs]

07:23.777 --> 07:30.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:35.205 --> 07:37.999
Hey, I just saw
the funniest thing at day care.

07:37.999 --> 07:40.752
Scout was annoyed that Luna
had this hedgehog toy,

07:40.752 --> 07:42.003
and he made this face.

07:42.003 --> 07:43.630
It looked exactly
like you look

07:43.630 --> 07:44.923
when you're annoyed with me.

07:44.923 --> 07:47.759
Excuse me.
Sam Sutton asked for you.

07:47.759 --> 07:49.302
He said it wasn't urgent, though.

07:49.302 --> 07:51.096
Yeah, I just saw him.

07:51.096 --> 07:53.139
No, he's asking
for Dr. Wilson.

07:53.139 --> 07:54.599
Oh.

07:55.433 --> 07:57.018
Mm.

07:57.018 --> 07:59.229
That's it.
That's the face.

07:59.229 --> 08:01.648
Wait, why--
why are you annoyed with me?

08:01.648 --> 08:03.233
[sighs]

08:03.233 --> 08:05.318
Don't you think
it's a little inappropriate

08:05.318 --> 08:07.237
to tell a patient
that you're single?

08:07.237 --> 08:09.656
He asked, and he thought
he was gonna die.

08:09.656 --> 08:12.283
He said you have
Disney princess eyes.

08:12.283 --> 08:13.702
You think I don't?

08:14.994 --> 08:16.788
I'm kidding.
I'm kidding.

08:16.788 --> 08:18.998
I appreciate
the misplaced chivalry,

08:18.998 --> 08:20.250
but do you remember
how many times

08:20.250 --> 08:21.501
I would get hit on
at Jimmy's Crab Shack?

08:21.501 --> 08:23.378
- [chuckles]
- I think I can handle myself.

08:23.378 --> 08:25.422
<i>Dr. Angle
to the Psych Unit.</i>

08:25.422 --> 08:27.799
<i>Dr Lea Engle
to the Psych Unit.</i>

08:27.799 --> 08:29.676
Ray, can we just stop
and talk about this?

08:29.676 --> 08:32.470
Look, you said I didn't need
the surgery right now.

08:32.470 --> 08:34.597
Right now and never
are two very different things,

08:34.597 --> 08:36.725
plus that was two months
and three failed attempts

08:36.725 --> 08:37.809
at surgery ago.

08:37.809 --> 08:39.269
Okay, well, I'm still alive,

08:39.269 --> 08:42.939
so I'm good, great,
fantastic, really.

08:42.939 --> 08:45.567
You have a weakened aorta,
which supplies blood

08:45.567 --> 08:47.652
to all of your major organs.
If it bursts--

08:47.652 --> 08:49.070
I know, okay?
You told me.

08:49.070 --> 08:50.321
But those consent forms,

08:50.321 --> 08:52.323
they say
I could have renal failure

08:52.323 --> 08:54.701
or heart problems
or bleed out during surgery.

08:54.701 --> 08:55.952
No, thanks.

08:55.952 --> 08:57.620
There is a less than
5% chance

08:57.620 --> 08:59.831
of renal failure, bleeding out,
or heart problems,

08:59.831 --> 09:01.833
but there is a 10% chance

09:01.833 --> 09:04.127
that your aneurysm will rupture
at any moment,

09:04.127 --> 09:06.379
and if that happens,
your chances of survival

09:06.379 --> 09:08.965
are worse than all
of these numbers combined.

09:08.965 --> 09:11.718
Okay, just stop.
Just stop.

09:11.718 --> 09:14.095
I don't know
about all the statistics,

09:14.095 --> 09:16.723
but what I do know
is that those consent forms

09:16.723 --> 09:18.892
say I could die
a dozen different ways

09:18.892 --> 09:20.560
if I do the surgery.

09:20.560 --> 09:21.895
I'm an illustrator.

09:21.895 --> 09:23.688
I sit at a desk all day.

09:23.688 --> 09:25.774
It doesn't require
much exertion.

09:25.774 --> 09:28.526
At this point,
it might not take much.

09:28.526 --> 09:30.779
I'll take my chances.

09:30.779 --> 09:33.323
Those chances would be
so much better with surgery.

09:33.323 --> 09:35.533
You can't force me
to do this.

09:35.533 --> 09:37.327
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

09:37.327 --> 09:39.537
- Ray.
- So we just let him go?

09:39.537 --> 09:42.624
- He's a ticking time bomb.
- Informed consent.

09:42.624 --> 09:45.085
We can't force a patient
to get a procedure.

09:45.085 --> 09:46.544
His mom will work on him,

09:46.544 --> 09:47.962
and hopefully
he will come back.

09:47.962 --> 09:50.423
All right, you two,
go to the skills lab,

09:50.423 --> 09:51.758
and I will page you
if something comes up.

09:51.758 --> 09:55.095
Mm.
Coming?

09:55.095 --> 09:57.514
Yeah, go ahead.
I'll catch up.

09:57.514 --> 10:02.393
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:02.393 --> 10:05.105
- Hey, you were looking for me.
- I was.

10:05.105 --> 10:10.485
I have a question about the--
the, uh, the plate

10:10.485 --> 10:14.364
that you put in my arm, and--

10:14.364 --> 10:16.533
okay, yeah, obviously,
I don't really have a question.

10:16.533 --> 10:19.077
I just wanted to see you
so I could thank you.

10:19.077 --> 10:21.496
- For what?
- Saving my life.

10:21.496 --> 10:23.915
Okay, I know that post-op
can be boring--

10:23.915 --> 10:25.917
It is.
It is so boring.

10:25.917 --> 10:28.128
I thought I could
flirt with you

10:28.128 --> 10:29.295
while we play a game of cards.

10:29.295 --> 10:31.881
You'd be holding all the cards
for real.

10:31.881 --> 10:35.385
Well, my day
is anything but boring, so...

10:35.385 --> 10:37.095
Okay, okay,
go cut people open.

10:37.095 --> 10:39.264
I'll be here all week.
We have time.

10:39.264 --> 10:41.141
Actually,
I'm delivering twins.

10:41.141 --> 10:43.768
I am both an OB-GYN
and a general surgeon.

10:43.768 --> 10:45.854
You're pretty
and multitalented.

10:45.854 --> 10:47.689
We are a rare breed.

10:49.315 --> 10:52.986
Uh, so what do you do now
that you're no longer military?

10:52.986 --> 10:55.321
Oh, I'm still a pilot,
just not military.

10:55.321 --> 10:57.157
So flying hundreds of people
through the air

10:57.157 --> 10:58.616
wasn't terrifying enough.

10:58.616 --> 11:00.076
You had to put on
a shiny sleeping bag

11:00.076 --> 11:01.703
and jump out of a plane.

11:01.703 --> 11:04.247
I'm actually
a pretty simple guy.

11:04.247 --> 11:06.958
Yeah, because simple guys
are always

11:06.958 --> 11:10.753
jumping off of pyramids
and rainforest cliffs, or--

11:10.753 --> 11:13.631
You stalked my social media.

11:13.631 --> 11:18.011
I wanted to know
what wingsuiting was.

11:18.011 --> 11:19.846
[clears throat]

11:19.846 --> 11:22.015
Um, I have to get back to OB.

11:22.015 --> 11:23.850
Is there anything else
that you need?

11:23.850 --> 11:25.018
Not at the moment,

11:25.018 --> 11:26.394
but I will keep
your offer in mind.

11:30.190 --> 11:31.983
You realize
that she meant medically?

11:34.360 --> 11:37.030
- No, she didn't.
- [sighs]

11:42.535 --> 11:44.412
Ray, hi.

11:44.412 --> 11:46.664
- Uh, can I have a minute.
- Oh, my God.

11:46.664 --> 11:48.750
Stop with the consent forms.

11:48.750 --> 11:50.376
What, do you get a commission
on the surgery or something?

11:50.376 --> 11:53.254
Uh, no, no, no commission.
Just my notes.

11:53.254 --> 11:55.173
- I just want to talk.
- Yeah.

11:55.173 --> 11:56.758
You mean talk me
into the surgery.

11:56.758 --> 11:59.594
No, no, no,
talk about the surgery.

11:59.594 --> 12:02.513
Okay, it's your decision.
I just--

12:02.513 --> 12:03.765
I won't be able to sleep

12:03.765 --> 12:05.516
knowing I didn't do
everything I could

12:05.516 --> 12:08.686
to make sure you were informed.
Let's just take a walk, okay?

12:08.686 --> 12:12.065
You're leaving anyway, right?
I could use some fresh air.

12:14.484 --> 12:16.277
[sighs]

12:16.277 --> 12:17.445
Are you coming?

12:17.445 --> 12:21.074
<i>Dr. Brooks to Oncology.</i>

12:21.074 --> 12:25.036
- We got you one with a window.
- Oh, how nice.

12:27.914 --> 12:29.916
[together]
Surprise!

12:29.916 --> 12:32.293
Norma, Lois!

12:32.293 --> 12:35.296
- Welcome to your new room.
- Did we scare you?

12:35.296 --> 12:37.674
I didn't want to yell,
but Norma made me.

12:37.674 --> 12:40.009
I'm fine.
I loved it!

12:40.009 --> 12:41.719
Come here, you two.

12:41.719 --> 12:43.721
[laughter]

12:43.721 --> 12:45.014
both: Mwah!

12:45.014 --> 12:46.933
I told them they could
only stay for an hour.

12:46.933 --> 12:49.018
- You need to get your rest.
- Oh, don't listen to Jules.

12:49.018 --> 12:50.645
She's in doctor mode.

12:50.645 --> 12:54.691
Speaking of Jules,
we brought your crochet bag.

12:54.691 --> 12:57.735
You know, my treble stitch
is getting much better.

12:57.735 --> 13:01.155
Wow, nice,
but that's a half double.

13:01.155 --> 13:03.741
I can show you the treble
this afternoon again.

13:03.741 --> 13:05.451
Oh, you see
how she talks to me?

13:05.451 --> 13:07.996
She's an angel,
if a doctor can be an angel,

13:07.996 --> 13:09.414
like in that movie.

13:09.414 --> 13:12.166
Oh, we put your toiletries
in the bathroom.

13:12.166 --> 13:15.420
Oh, thank heavens.
My hair needs a good brushing.

13:15.420 --> 13:18.298
- "Angel Doctor."
- That's not a movie.

13:18.298 --> 13:20.300
- Uh, "Doctor Angel."
- That's not a movie either.

13:20.300 --> 13:21.884
- Max.
- I'm fine. I'm fine.

13:21.884 --> 13:23.636
- Okay, okay.
- Thanks.

13:23.636 --> 13:25.763
Oh, Doc.

13:25.763 --> 13:28.099
- Her color's good.
- How's her appetite?

13:28.099 --> 13:29.350
Uh, it's back.
Her appetite--

13:29.350 --> 13:31.185
Ow!
[loud thuds]

13:31.185 --> 13:32.854
- Max.
- [grunts]

13:32.854 --> 13:34.897
Oh, Max, are you okay?

13:34.897 --> 13:37.191
[gasps]

13:37.191 --> 13:40.862
I--I--I don't know.
Am I?

13:40.862 --> 13:43.823
Okay, all right.

13:43.823 --> 13:46.242
Okay, just take deep breaths.

13:46.242 --> 13:47.827
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

13:53.374 --> 13:55.668
- Winston.
- Hey.

13:55.668 --> 14:00.715
Will it be awkward for you
seeing Maggie so soon?

14:00.715 --> 14:03.843
It'll definitely be awkward, yeah.

14:03.843 --> 14:06.054
But, uh,
you're coming anyway.

14:06.054 --> 14:09.265
Very few Black men have been
nominated for this award...

14:09.265 --> 14:11.184
- [sighs]
- So I'll be there.

14:11.184 --> 14:12.477
I'm proud of you, son.

14:14.270 --> 14:15.813
I'm proud of me too.
[phone chimes]

14:15.813 --> 14:17.440
- Excuse me, a consult.
- Okay.

14:20.568 --> 14:22.904
[taps]

14:22.904 --> 14:25.281
The Catherine Fox Award
means something

14:25.281 --> 14:27.325
to people around here.

14:27.325 --> 14:31.579
You know, if Winston can rise
and face Maggie,

14:31.579 --> 14:34.791
I think you'll be able
to handle seeing Meredith.

14:34.791 --> 14:36.626
Dr. Webber, I don't believe

14:36.626 --> 14:38.586
in ranking
medical contributions.

14:38.586 --> 14:40.171
I just don't.

14:40.171 --> 14:41.422
I also don't feel the need
to go all the way to Boston

14:41.422 --> 14:43.049
for some rubber chicken dinner.

14:43.049 --> 14:44.634
Listen, I'm sorry, but
it's a little presumptuous--

14:44.634 --> 14:47.220
Your absence would be
an insult to this hospital,

14:47.220 --> 14:49.055
your fellow nominees,
and my wife

14:49.055 --> 14:51.224
for who the award is named,
so I suggest

14:51.224 --> 14:53.226
you get off
your moral high ground,

14:53.226 --> 14:55.061
set aside your feelings
about Boston,

14:55.061 --> 14:58.564
do your job, and join us.

14:58.564 --> 15:00.441
<i>Dr. Olivares to Labor
and Delivery.</i>

15:00.441 --> 15:01.526
<i>Dr. Olivares
to Labor and Delivery.</i>

15:01.526 --> 15:03.152
[sighs]

15:03.152 --> 15:05.947
Floor wasn't even slippery.

15:05.947 --> 15:07.615
There weren't any obstacles.

15:07.615 --> 15:11.035
I was just walking to the sink.

15:11.035 --> 15:12.620
- Ow.
- What do you see, Millin?

15:12.620 --> 15:14.205
Uh, she has a fractured rib,

15:14.205 --> 15:16.249
which explains her pain
when she moves her upper body.

15:16.249 --> 15:17.500
What's the treatment
for that?

15:17.500 --> 15:19.043
Rest.
It should heal on its own.

15:19.043 --> 15:20.294
What about her head?

15:20.294 --> 15:22.046
The cut
doesn't appear serious,

15:22.046 --> 15:23.256
but I'd like to get a scan.

15:23.256 --> 15:26.884
So let's get her up to CT
and page Neuro.

15:26.884 --> 15:30.638
- Maxine--
- I'm not up to visitors today.

15:30.638 --> 15:33.474
I think you two better go.

15:33.474 --> 15:35.268
I'll be here, and I will call
with any updates.

15:35.268 --> 15:36.519
I promise.

15:36.519 --> 15:39.564
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

15:39.564 --> 15:45.361
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:45.361 --> 15:48.072
Left open comminuted
humeral fracture,

15:48.072 --> 15:49.532
right open femoral fracture...

15:49.532 --> 15:51.033
Do you always narrate
your data input?

15:51.033 --> 15:52.952
Helps keep me accurate.
What are you working on?

15:52.952 --> 15:54.453
I'm watching
an old triple A surgery

15:54.453 --> 15:55.580
while double checking
the wedding spreadsheet

15:55.580 --> 15:56.706
for the RSVPs.

15:56.706 --> 15:57.707
Oh,
you know I'm coming, right?

15:57.707 --> 15:59.000
Never sent in a card.

15:59.000 --> 16:01.377
I live with you.
It was assumed.

16:01.377 --> 16:02.753
Adams isn't coming.

16:02.753 --> 16:05.339
That is different,
and you know it.

16:05.339 --> 16:07.425
- You bringing a plus one?
- [sighs]

16:07.425 --> 16:08.968
Did you even read
the invitation?

16:08.968 --> 16:11.053
I was working two jobs.

16:11.053 --> 16:13.306
It's this weekend,
right, isn't it?

16:13.306 --> 16:16.184
- Why'd you move it up again?
- Grandma's getting worse.

16:16.184 --> 16:17.810
She's got maybe a good
90 minutes in the morning,

16:17.810 --> 16:19.937
- and that time is shrinking.
- That's rough.

16:19.937 --> 16:20.897
You know what
she remembers though?

16:20.897 --> 16:22.648
Weddings, she loves them,

16:22.648 --> 16:25.193
the colors, the flowers,
the favors.

16:25.193 --> 16:26.611
We actually have conversations
about the wedding

16:26.611 --> 16:28.821
that feel completely real.

16:28.821 --> 16:31.449
- Hi.
- Hi.

16:31.449 --> 16:34.368
I'm just gonna take
a look around.

16:34.368 --> 16:36.996
- How's the new space?
- Can't complain.

16:41.292 --> 16:43.127
- Is everything okay?
- I don't know, let me think.

16:43.127 --> 16:44.754
You complained to Altman
about a job

16:44.754 --> 16:46.214
you haven't worked at
for months.

16:46.214 --> 16:48.799
You projected your own trauma
onto my situation

16:48.799 --> 16:50.176
resulting in half
of the surgical chiefs

16:50.176 --> 16:52.178
- meeting about me.
- I'm sorry.

16:52.178 --> 16:57.058
- I--how can I make it up to you?
- I'll get over it.

16:57.058 --> 17:00.019
I just need to be mad at you
for a minute.

17:00.019 --> 17:02.897
- Is that a literal minute or--
- Figurative.

17:02.897 --> 17:04.899
Right.
[chuckles]

17:04.899 --> 17:06.525
I'm just gonna...

17:12.323 --> 17:14.200
I always thought
you two had chemistry.

17:14.200 --> 17:15.993
What, me and Helm?
Why?

17:15.993 --> 17:17.745
- She hasn't made a move.
- You could.

17:17.745 --> 17:19.497
I don't like rejection.

17:19.497 --> 17:21.666
I once had very embarrassing,
somewhat traumatic rejection

17:21.666 --> 17:25.002
during a prom-posal go viral
at my high school.

17:25.002 --> 17:26.212
I don't make
the first move anymore,

17:26.212 --> 17:27.463
and it's worked out fine
for me.

17:27.463 --> 17:30.216
Okay.

17:30.216 --> 17:32.051
Who's your plus one again?

17:32.051 --> 17:35.054
<i>[quirky music]</i>

17:35.054 --> 17:38.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:38.099 --> 17:41.060
So you're
an illustrator, huh?

17:41.060 --> 17:44.522
Yeah, yeah, graphic novels.

17:44.522 --> 17:48.276
I draw, and my friend Sunita
writes the stories.

17:48.276 --> 17:50.111
We're working on one right now
about a kid

17:50.111 --> 17:54.073
whose big brother is afraid
to die before he turns 30,

17:54.073 --> 17:56.742
so they're building a portal
to a parallel universe

17:56.742 --> 17:59.579
so that they could time jump
and that he could turn 31

17:59.579 --> 18:02.206
and then reenter
the real world.

18:02.206 --> 18:04.083
Cool.

18:04.083 --> 18:06.752
- Also very specific.
- [chuckles]

18:06.752 --> 18:09.589
I had a really vivid dream
when I was a kid.

18:09.589 --> 18:13.718
Um, my grandpa
who died before I was born

18:13.718 --> 18:16.178
sat at the edge of my bed
and told me

18:16.178 --> 18:18.222
we'd be together
for my 30th birthday.

18:18.222 --> 18:19.223
[chuckles]

18:19.223 --> 18:21.934
It scared the crap out of me,

18:21.934 --> 18:24.604
so I've never smoked.
I don't drink.

18:24.604 --> 18:26.814
I stopped eating meat.
Hell, I don't even drive.

18:26.814 --> 18:28.482
I take public transit.

18:28.482 --> 18:30.443
And maybe
it's completely irrational,

18:30.443 --> 18:33.154
but I always thought,
if I could just make it

18:33.154 --> 18:36.574
past 30 I'll be okay.

18:36.574 --> 18:41.621
I need to stay alive
for my mom,

18:41.621 --> 18:43.789
and I'm helping with
my sister's college tuition,

18:43.789 --> 18:45.333
so I can't die.

18:47.877 --> 18:49.545
I don't wanna die.

18:52.965 --> 18:54.634
I don't want that either.

18:56.719 --> 18:59.347
Look, I'm not a professional
like you,

18:59.347 --> 19:01.390
but here is your aorta.

19:01.390 --> 19:04.143
Dr. Adams, look, I appreciate
what you're trying to do.

19:04.143 --> 19:05.311
Look, the statistics
freak you out,

19:05.311 --> 19:06.437
so let's draw it.

19:08.689 --> 19:11.192
Okay, so we'll access
your aorta through your groin,

19:11.192 --> 19:13.319
and then we'll thread
a small wire

19:13.319 --> 19:15.071
up through
the abdominal aneurysm,

19:15.071 --> 19:16.739
and then we'll deploy a graft,

19:16.739 --> 19:19.367
which will expand
to reinforce the weak area

19:19.367 --> 19:22.495
and simulate an artery,
which will allow blood

19:22.495 --> 19:24.955
- to flow through safely.
- Is that a potato?

19:24.955 --> 19:27.375
- That's a kidney.
- With a Slinky?

19:27.375 --> 19:29.960
- That's the graft.
- [laughs]

19:29.960 --> 19:32.254
Bruh, you suck at drawing.

19:32.254 --> 19:34.590
[chuckles]
Fair.

19:34.590 --> 19:37.677
But I promise

19:37.677 --> 19:40.680
this procedure has been tested
over and over,

19:40.680 --> 19:43.057
and if a problem comes up
like you mentioned,

19:43.057 --> 19:45.059
we have ways to address it.

19:45.059 --> 19:48.479
What we can't do is be with you
if the aneurysm ruptures

19:48.479 --> 19:49.313
while you're at home.

19:52.692 --> 19:55.194
<i>Did you feel dizzy before
you fell, Mrs. Anderson?</i>

19:55.194 --> 19:57.113
I don't think so.

19:57.113 --> 19:59.824
<i>I just remember
losing my balance</i>

19:59.824 --> 20:02.868
<i>and stupidly hitting
my head on the sink.</i>

20:02.868 --> 20:04.203
Maybe it's a sign.

20:04.203 --> 20:05.746
Loss of balance
can be a symptom

20:05.746 --> 20:07.248
of a variety of conditions.

20:07.248 --> 20:09.333
Or a sign that my time is up.

20:09.333 --> 20:11.877
When the racehorse
breaks its leg,

20:11.877 --> 20:13.254
they usually put it down.

20:13.254 --> 20:14.880
Max, you're not a racehorse.

20:14.880 --> 20:16.841
<i>No, not anymore.</i>

20:16.841 --> 20:20.594
Oh, an active brain bleed
in the subdural space.

20:20.594 --> 20:22.012
We should prep
for a decompression.

20:22.012 --> 20:23.639
- Kwan, book an OR.
- On it.

20:23.639 --> 20:25.766
Uh, Dr. Shepherd, could I
scrub in if that's okay?

20:25.766 --> 20:27.727
Uh, no, it's not.

20:27.727 --> 20:30.271
You were on neuro this morning,
and you traded with Kwan.

20:30.271 --> 20:32.982
- I could trade back.
- You will do no such thing.

20:32.982 --> 20:34.233
What is happening here?

20:34.233 --> 20:36.235
Ah, Millin just confirmed
my suspicion

20:36.235 --> 20:37.611
that she's too close
to the patient

20:37.611 --> 20:39.405
- to be her doctor.
- What? No, no.

20:39.405 --> 20:40.823
I just--she's talking about
being euthanized

20:40.823 --> 20:42.241
like an animal.

20:42.241 --> 20:43.868
Look me in the eye
and tell me

20:43.868 --> 20:47.037
that you do not consider
that woman family.

20:47.037 --> 20:48.205
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

20:48.205 --> 20:50.875
Mm-hmm, you're off the case
for good.

20:50.875 --> 20:57.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:02.803 --> 21:04.555
- Dr. Altman.
- Yes, yes.

21:04.555 --> 21:06.766
We're all very excited.
Thanks, Catherine.

21:06.766 --> 21:08.768
You know, technically,
Grey Sloan can claim

21:08.768 --> 21:10.561
three Catherine Fox
Award nominees

21:10.561 --> 21:12.104
since Pierce performed
her transplant here.

21:12.104 --> 21:13.522
That's great.
About Ray--

21:13.522 --> 21:15.941
Yeah, I know
it can be disappointing.

21:15.941 --> 21:17.735
Sometimes patients
just don't understand,

21:17.735 --> 21:20.404
but there will be
other triple As to repair.

21:20.404 --> 21:22.198
Yeah, but I still think
we should do Ray's.

21:22.198 --> 21:23.991
He signed the consent forms.

21:23.991 --> 21:28.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:28.496 --> 21:30.873
Page Griffith,
and let's get him to radiology

21:30.873 --> 21:33.334
before he bolts again.
Well done.

21:33.334 --> 21:40.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:40.341 --> 21:43.969
- Oh.
- Seriously?

21:43.969 --> 21:46.096
You're lucky the twins' mom
is still dilating.

21:46.096 --> 21:47.640
- What is it?
- I have an itch to scratch.

21:47.640 --> 21:50.059
No, literally, it's--
help.

21:50.059 --> 21:51.727
This is what orderlies
are for.

21:51.727 --> 21:52.978
I know.

21:52.978 --> 21:54.355
I could've called
somebody else,

21:54.355 --> 21:56.816
but then you wouldn't be here.

21:56.816 --> 21:58.692
Don't move.

21:58.692 --> 22:00.402
Okay.
That?

22:00.402 --> 22:02.822
Oh, you are the best doctor
I've ever had in my life.

22:02.822 --> 22:06.242
If you ask for a sponge bath,
I'm leaving.

22:06.242 --> 22:08.786
You know,
last time I had a cast,

22:08.786 --> 22:10.496
they let me pick the colors.

22:10.496 --> 22:12.248
[laughs]
How old were you?

22:12.248 --> 22:14.250
Seven.
Fell off the monkey bars.

22:14.250 --> 22:15.543
You had a death wish
even then, huh?

22:15.543 --> 22:17.253
I was so bummed.

22:17.253 --> 22:20.631
My dad was taking me
to my first pro ball game.

22:20.631 --> 22:23.217
I had been practicing catching
fly balls for three months.

22:23.217 --> 22:24.760
Glove doesn't fit
over the cast.

22:24.760 --> 22:26.428
Can't catch anything.

22:26.428 --> 22:27.930
But the first baseman
saw me in the stands,

22:27.930 --> 22:30.558
ran over, signed my cast.

22:30.558 --> 22:32.643
I cried when they cut it off.

22:32.643 --> 22:34.436
<i>[quirky music]</i>

22:34.436 --> 22:37.231
Well, you're, uh, lucky
with all the dumb stuff you do

22:37.231 --> 22:39.441
that you haven't had
a cast since.

22:39.441 --> 22:43.362
Yeah, I have had
half a dozen surgeries

22:43.362 --> 22:45.948
and one metal plate,
but yeah, no casts.

22:45.948 --> 22:48.951
[exhales]
[phone chimes]

22:48.951 --> 22:49.910
- The twins.
- Oh.

22:49.910 --> 22:52.580
- Gotta go.
- Lucky bastards.

22:52.580 --> 22:56.041
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:56.041 --> 22:58.252
[applause]

22:58.252 --> 23:00.045
Thank you.
Thank you so much.

23:00.045 --> 23:02.214
I'm--hey,
I'm glad to be nominated.

23:02.214 --> 23:03.591
[applause]

23:03.591 --> 23:05.342
Do you know
how many codes I ran

23:05.342 --> 23:06.760
to save lives
in the ER last year?

23:06.760 --> 23:08.679
- Where's my award for that?
- For doing your job?

23:08.679 --> 23:09.930
He was doing his.

23:09.930 --> 23:11.515
My research is helping
to cure Parkinson's.

23:11.515 --> 23:13.142
You don't see me nominated
for anything.

23:13.142 --> 23:17.730
Listen to you two complaining
about your lack of recognition.

23:17.730 --> 23:19.148
You're right.

23:19.148 --> 23:21.233
We're happy for him
and Marsh.

23:21.233 --> 23:23.068
I mean, I oversaw

23:23.068 --> 23:26.530
a simultaneous
12-person domino surgery

23:26.530 --> 23:30.117
wherein six people
got new kidneys.

23:30.117 --> 23:33.746
You know,
I used deactivated HIV

23:33.746 --> 23:36.707
to save a boy with SCID.

23:36.707 --> 23:40.669
I mean, I spearheaded changes
in post-op protocols

23:40.669 --> 23:45.341
to reduce post-op fistulas,
basically curing the problem.

23:45.341 --> 23:47.051
If anyone should ask,
"Where's my award?"

23:47.051 --> 23:48.636
it's me.

23:48.636 --> 23:51.347
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:51.347 --> 23:54.266
- I was almost out of here.
- You will be soon.

23:54.266 --> 23:56.727
Dr. Shepherd has done
a lot of these.

23:56.727 --> 24:00.147
You're drilling into
my 81-year-old skull, right?

24:00.147 --> 24:02.232
If it were only me,
I'd tell you to put me

24:02.232 --> 24:04.693
out of my misery
and send me to the farm.

24:04.693 --> 24:07.988
I talked to Norma about Jules.

24:07.988 --> 24:10.491
I said she was
an excellent roommate.

24:10.491 --> 24:12.368
Not sure I can say the same
about Norma.

24:12.368 --> 24:14.787
That woman snores
like a freight train.

24:14.787 --> 24:16.288
[laughs]

24:16.288 --> 24:17.998
Let's hope
it doesn't come to that.

24:17.998 --> 24:20.751
I know that Jules
loves living with you.

24:20.751 --> 24:22.294
Mm.

24:22.294 --> 24:26.757
Pete, my son,
he went to college

24:26.757 --> 24:30.052
right after my husband
and I divorced.

24:30.052 --> 24:32.554
I brought him up
to be independent,

24:32.554 --> 24:37.267
which was maybe my excuse
for not being more involved.

24:37.267 --> 24:39.103
By the way, it worked.

24:39.103 --> 24:41.939
He graduated
and moved to London.

24:41.939 --> 24:43.565
I hardly ever see him anymore.

24:43.565 --> 24:47.361
He doesn't need
my homemade split pea soup

24:47.361 --> 24:51.532
or my special herbal teas
to ward off colds

24:51.532 --> 24:56.120
or my hugs after a long day...

24:56.120 --> 25:00.457
but Jules,
she needs all of those things.

25:00.457 --> 25:04.378
It seems she didn't have them
when she was a child,

25:04.378 --> 25:06.463
and now I get to give them
to her.

25:08.257 --> 25:11.635
- She's lucky to have you.
- [chuckles]

25:11.635 --> 25:12.886
I'm the lucky one.

25:12.886 --> 25:15.597
[elevator dings]

25:15.597 --> 25:18.600
<i>[tender music]</i>

25:18.600 --> 25:25.024
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:25.024 --> 25:27.443
<i>What did you do
to convince him?</i>

25:27.443 --> 25:29.445
I drew a bad picture.

25:29.445 --> 25:31.947
I thought he'd respond
to a different approach.

25:33.407 --> 25:35.367
Chief, I just wanted
to say thanks

25:35.367 --> 25:37.119
for funding
the intern skills practicum.

25:37.119 --> 25:38.412
- I appreciate it.
- Of course.

25:38.412 --> 25:40.247
And congrats, again,
on the nomination.

25:40.247 --> 25:41.874
Sure, yeah.

25:41.874 --> 25:43.500
Oh, uh, Richard wanted me
to ask you about the dinner--

25:43.500 --> 25:44.710
No, count me out on that.

25:44.710 --> 25:46.920
[groaning]

25:46.920 --> 25:49.173
Ray, what's wrong?

25:49.173 --> 25:50.716
<i>My back, it really hurts.</i>

25:50.716 --> 25:53.343
Something's wrong.

25:53.343 --> 25:55.596
Damn it.

25:55.596 --> 25:57.848
- Oh, my God, is that a--
- It's a rupture. Come on.

25:57.848 --> 25:59.975
Code blue!

25:59.975 --> 26:01.894
<i>Code blue, Radiology.
Third floor.</i>

26:01.894 --> 26:03.437
Call the blood bank.
Activate an MTP.

26:03.437 --> 26:04.438
Let's go, let's go, let's go.

26:04.438 --> 26:05.689
<i>[Lxandra's "The Elephant"]</i>

26:05.689 --> 26:07.316
<i>♪ Somehow ♪</i>

26:07.316 --> 26:08.567
- I need a vascular setup.
- I'll assist.

26:08.567 --> 26:10.944
- Alert the OR!
- There's no time.

26:10.944 --> 26:12.988
- I'm opening him up right now.
- On the CT table?

26:12.988 --> 26:14.156
There's nowhere else.
You heard Altman.

26:14.156 --> 26:15.949
Let's go.
Come on, let's go.

26:15.949 --> 26:19.953
Come on.
Come on, Ray.

26:19.953 --> 26:21.789
Betadine, let's go.

26:21.789 --> 26:23.791
All right,
I need suction setup.

26:23.791 --> 26:26.293
Lap pad.
Ten blade.

26:26.293 --> 26:28.378
<i>♪ What are you gonna do? ♪</i>

26:28.378 --> 26:31.590
Here we go.
Stop compressions.

26:31.590 --> 26:38.138
<i>♪ Oh,
can't hide the skeletons ♪</i>

26:38.138 --> 26:39.723
<i>♪ Oh-oh ♪</i>

26:39.723 --> 26:41.558
More irrigation, please.

26:41.558 --> 26:42.684
<i>♪ This is hell
out on the loose ♪</i>

26:42.684 --> 26:45.229
Almost through.

26:45.229 --> 26:47.981
We need to hang more blood.

26:47.981 --> 26:50.776
I need better visualization.

26:50.776 --> 26:52.820
Keep the compressions coming.

26:52.820 --> 26:56.532
<i>♪ From a shallow grave,
every choice you made ♪</i>

26:56.532 --> 27:00.744
<i>♪ Shaking the ground,
ground, ground, ground ♪</i>

27:00.744 --> 27:03.539
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:03.539 --> 27:06.583
<i>♪ Hold on ♪</i>

27:06.583 --> 27:09.211
- Still no pulse.
- Scissors.

27:09.211 --> 27:11.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:11.130 --> 27:12.965
All right, got it. Clamp.

27:12.965 --> 27:17.010
<i>♪ Running out on you ♪</i>

27:17.010 --> 27:19.263
<i>♪ Do you feel it? ♪</i>

27:19.263 --> 27:23.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:23.308 --> 27:25.686
<i>♪ Can't cage the elephant ♪</i>

27:25.686 --> 27:27.437
All right, more lap pads.

27:27.437 --> 27:30.023
<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

27:30.023 --> 27:33.485
<i>♪ What are you gonna do? ♪</i>

27:33.485 --> 27:34.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:34.653 --> 27:37.322
<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

27:37.322 --> 27:41.201
<i>♪ Can't hide the skeletons ♪</i>

27:41.201 --> 27:44.121
<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

27:44.121 --> 27:46.373
<i>♪ This is hell
out on the loose ♪</i>

27:46.373 --> 27:49.001
Charge at 200.

27:49.001 --> 27:52.087
All right, clear.
Come on, come on, come on.

27:52.087 --> 27:55.382
Charge again to 200. Clear.

27:55.382 --> 27:56.425
<i>[defibrillator humming
and thudding]</i>

27:56.425 --> 27:58.719
Come on.

27:58.719 --> 28:00.220
Damn it.
Let me in there.

28:00.220 --> 28:03.015
Come on.
Come on.

28:03.015 --> 28:05.267
- Altman.
- He's 29 years old.

28:05.267 --> 28:06.685
I know.
We did everything we could.

28:06.685 --> 28:08.937
Come on.

28:08.937 --> 28:11.440
<i>♪ This is hell
out on the loose ♪</i>

28:11.440 --> 28:13.692
Beautiful work, Dr. Shepherd.

28:13.692 --> 28:16.653
<i>♪ Can't hide the skeletons ♪</i>

28:16.653 --> 28:18.906
<i>♪ Oh ♪</i>

28:18.906 --> 28:21.742
<i>♪ This is hell
out on the loose ♪</i>

28:21.742 --> 28:23.911
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:23.911 --> 28:25.120
Time of death...

28:25.120 --> 28:26.580
[heart monitor droning]

28:26.580 --> 28:28.957
15:21.

28:37.716 --> 28:40.719
<i>[tense music]</i>

28:40.719 --> 28:45.349
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:49.853 --> 28:52.481
Dr. Webber, hi.
Exciting news this morning.

28:52.481 --> 28:54.524
Well, I wish everyone
shared your enthusiasm.

28:54.524 --> 28:57.027
Well, you know
who loves awards? Helm.

28:57.027 --> 28:59.237
- Oh, she does, huh?
- I don't know.

28:59.237 --> 29:00.697
I'm just looking
for a good segue.

29:00.697 --> 29:02.699
- Ah.
- How did things go with her?

29:02.699 --> 29:04.117
She said
she'd think about it.

29:04.117 --> 29:05.744
Did she seem upbeat?

29:05.744 --> 29:07.537
Well, honestly,
she was asking for things

29:07.537 --> 29:10.248
- we hadn't done before.
- Were they unreasonable?

29:10.248 --> 29:12.918
Well, not terribly,
I suppose, but--

29:12.918 --> 29:14.252
With all due respect, sir,

29:14.252 --> 29:16.296
I don't see
why this is a question.

29:16.296 --> 29:18.548
This hospital is bursting
at the seams with patients

29:18.548 --> 29:21.510
and not enough doctors.
Helm is a proven asset.

29:21.510 --> 29:23.220
You know exactly
what you're getting with her,

29:23.220 --> 29:24.638
because you trained her.

29:24.638 --> 29:26.264
You've worked with her
long enough to know

29:26.264 --> 29:29.351
her talent and her dedication,
and frankly, sir,

29:29.351 --> 29:32.854
we need more senior residents,
so please, please,

29:32.854 --> 29:34.606
just give her what she wants.

29:34.606 --> 29:35.941
<i>Nurse Kingsbury to Five West</i>

29:35.941 --> 29:37.818
<i>Nurse Kingsbury to Five West.</i>

29:37.818 --> 29:41.613
Again, it ruptured, and we
couldn't control the bleeding.

29:41.613 --> 29:43.240
<i>[sobbing]</i>

29:43.240 --> 29:46.410
I am very sorry,
Mrs. Sanchez.

29:46.410 --> 29:50.789
I...

29:50.789 --> 29:52.040
the hospital will mail

29:52.040 --> 29:54.960
your son's belongings
to you in Tempe.

29:54.960 --> 29:57.671
<i>Thank you, Doctor.</i>

29:57.671 --> 29:59.297
[phone beeps]

29:59.297 --> 30:01.508
Yeah, those calls
are never easy.

30:04.594 --> 30:07.097
Hey, you got him back
to the hospital.

30:08.807 --> 30:12.519
Adams, there's--
there's a thing with ADHD

30:12.519 --> 30:15.063
where we feel the losses
really deeply,

30:15.063 --> 30:17.983
so you have to take equal time

30:17.983 --> 30:19.151
to give yourself credit
when you win.

30:19.151 --> 30:22.988
You fought for him.
Hey, hey.

30:22.988 --> 30:28.243
You fought for him.
That matters.

30:28.243 --> 30:31.747
He knew in his gut
he was dying.

30:31.747 --> 30:33.248
He knew he wasn't gonna see 30.

30:35.584 --> 30:39.629
I knew in my gut
that I was different.

30:39.629 --> 30:41.715
There was something different
about me my whole life.

30:41.715 --> 30:45.469
I knew I wasn't just lazy,
which is what they called me.

30:45.469 --> 30:47.137
You know, I went down
a rabbit hole online,

30:47.137 --> 30:49.848
and I have pretty much
every single symptom.

30:51.933 --> 30:53.268
I mean, difficulty focusing,

30:53.268 --> 30:56.021
time blindness,
short attention span,

30:56.021 --> 30:57.939
and my family
is full of doctors.

30:57.939 --> 31:00.358
It's not like ADHD is rare.
You saw it.

31:00.358 --> 31:01.359
Why didn't they?

31:02.652 --> 31:03.695
[sighs]

31:06.656 --> 31:10.327
I--I think parents,
sometimes they see their kids

31:10.327 --> 31:11.703
through the lens
of their own experience.

31:11.703 --> 31:13.246
Your parents
were overachievers,

31:13.246 --> 31:14.998
so they expected you to be,
and when you weren't,

31:14.998 --> 31:17.000
they were so busy pushing
and pushing you to live up

31:17.000 --> 31:19.377
to your potential,
they didn't think to look

31:19.377 --> 31:22.089
for why you weren't

31:22.089 --> 31:23.965
Yeah, or maybe
they were just too busy

31:23.965 --> 31:25.092
being disappointed
in me,

31:25.092 --> 31:26.676
they didn't bother.

31:28.845 --> 31:30.430
[sighs]

31:35.352 --> 31:38.897
You know, I hope you win
the Catherine Fox Award.

31:40.649 --> 31:42.567
Why?

31:42.567 --> 31:47.155
I don't know,
because I feel like a failure,

31:47.155 --> 31:48.865
and I feel like
I caught this too late,

31:48.865 --> 31:50.492
and if you win, then--

31:50.492 --> 31:52.994
If I win,
we aren't just losers?

31:52.994 --> 31:54.496
Is that it?

31:54.496 --> 31:57.666
[chuckles]
Yeah, something like that.

31:57.666 --> 32:01.837
You know, Adams, this award,
it doesn't mean anything.

32:04.506 --> 32:05.924
If that's
your acceptance speech,

32:05.924 --> 32:08.718
- it's gonna need work.
- [laughs]

32:12.139 --> 32:13.932
How long does
a delivery usually take?

32:13.932 --> 32:16.476
- A couple hours?
- Like, from Postmates?

32:16.476 --> 32:19.312
- Never mind.
- Dude, you gotta take it easy.

32:19.312 --> 32:21.481
Women don't love
aggressive flirting,

32:21.481 --> 32:22.941
at least not from men.

32:22.941 --> 32:24.526
You don't get anywhere
if you don't ask.

32:24.526 --> 32:26.570
- You gotta at least ask.
- False alarm.

32:26.570 --> 32:28.947
- You paged her again?
- Wasn't me.

32:28.947 --> 32:30.323
The twins
do not want to come out.

32:30.323 --> 32:31.783
So you came back
to get cheered up

32:31.783 --> 32:33.785
- by your favorite patient.
- No.

32:33.785 --> 32:37.372
I was making sure
that Yasuda is checking...

32:37.372 --> 32:38.874
- I am.
- On--okay.

32:38.874 --> 32:39.916
Here.

32:42.919 --> 32:45.172
- That sounds...
- Weak.

32:45.172 --> 32:46.923
It does sound weak. Here.

32:46.923 --> 32:48.884
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

32:48.884 --> 32:51.052
Take this.
Ready?

32:51.052 --> 32:53.430
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:53.430 --> 32:55.515
- The flap's congested.
- What does that mean?

32:55.515 --> 32:58.143
We moved muscle
from the back of your leg

32:58.143 --> 33:00.687
- to the front to cover the bone.
- The flap.

33:00.687 --> 33:02.480
Yes.
Yasuda, what's happening?

33:02.480 --> 33:03.857
A hematoma,
it's putting pressure

33:03.857 --> 33:05.567
on the flap and cutting off
the blood supply.

33:05.567 --> 33:07.152
Why do I feel
like this is bad?

33:07.152 --> 33:09.196
- It is bad, if the flap dies.
- Is that gonna happen?

33:09.196 --> 33:11.448
- Not if I decompress it.
- Another surgery?

33:11.448 --> 33:12.657
We can do it right here
if you consent.

33:12.657 --> 33:13.992
Do it.
DO it.

33:13.992 --> 33:16.161
Yasuda,
push additional morphine.

33:16.161 --> 33:18.997
I'm good.
I have a high pain threshold.

33:18.997 --> 33:20.957
Plus I kind of want
to see this.

33:20.957 --> 33:23.793
Okay.
Ready?

33:23.793 --> 33:25.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:25.795 --> 33:28.256
[groans]

33:28.256 --> 33:30.091
- Okay, more gauze.
- Yeah.

33:30.091 --> 33:32.677
- Thank you.
- Okay.

33:32.677 --> 33:34.638
- [groans]
- Just breathe.

33:34.638 --> 33:37.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:44.231 --> 33:46.900
[knock at door]

33:48.360 --> 33:50.028
The decompression went well.

33:51.905 --> 33:54.616
I know those are a regift.
I'm the one who brought them.

33:54.616 --> 33:56.201
I thought you'd want
to keep these for Maxine

33:56.201 --> 33:57.410
while she's in the ICU.

33:59.454 --> 34:01.831
Or I could keep them
by the nurses' station.

34:01.831 --> 34:02.707
No, leave 'em there.

34:04.084 --> 34:06.211
Well, hopefully,
it won't be that long,

34:06.211 --> 34:08.838
and you can both
get out of here.

34:08.838 --> 34:12.050
I know what it feels like

34:12.050 --> 34:14.219
to sit by the side
of someone you love

34:14.219 --> 34:17.222
and worry
they're not gonna make it.

34:17.222 --> 34:20.100
I know that fear
and anger and grief.

34:21.810 --> 34:25.146
It's okay.
Professional distance and all.

34:25.146 --> 34:28.108
I'm just saying it's okay
to have those feelings.

34:29.943 --> 34:31.736
I'm here for you.

34:31.736 --> 34:33.989
I'm fine, Kwan.

34:33.989 --> 34:37.993
I need to call Norma and Lois.

34:48.712 --> 34:51.673
<i>[light dramatic music]</i>

34:51.673 --> 34:54.676
[sobbing]

34:54.676 --> 35:01.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:08.148 --> 35:09.691
I've done a lot
of cool things,

35:09.691 --> 35:13.445
but you just sliced into my leg
like it was nothing.

35:13.445 --> 35:16.364
- It's no swimming with sharks.
- Oh, you went deep.

35:16.364 --> 35:18.533
That post was from
at least three years ago.

35:18.533 --> 35:20.994
Wow, I never thought
I could be a third wheel

35:20.994 --> 35:22.954
- in a patient room.
- What was that, Yasuda?

35:22.954 --> 35:24.914
Nothing.

35:24.914 --> 35:27.292
Dr. Wilson,
OB called for you.

35:27.292 --> 35:29.794
Cathy Han is headed into L&D.

35:29.794 --> 35:31.212
- For real this time?
- I don't know.

35:31.212 --> 35:34.174
- I don't work up there.
- Okay.

35:34.174 --> 35:35.508
You just cut my leg open,

35:35.508 --> 35:37.010
and now you're about
to deliver twins?

35:37.010 --> 35:39.387
You are my hero.
Sign my cast.

35:40.889 --> 35:42.932
[sighs]

35:44.434 --> 35:47.812
- No tears when they remove it.
- No promises.

35:47.812 --> 35:48.897
[laughs]

35:51.816 --> 35:55.153
See?
You gotta at least ask.

35:58.406 --> 35:59.824
- Richard.
- Here you go.

35:59.824 --> 36:01.368
- Marsh.
- Yeah.

36:01.368 --> 36:03.203
- I care about this program.
- I do too.

36:03.203 --> 36:04.829
Not like I do.

36:04.829 --> 36:07.082
It's my legacy, and I need
to get it back to where it was,

36:07.082 --> 36:08.750
and a nomination
for our residency director

36:08.750 --> 36:10.669
is a big deal.

36:10.669 --> 36:13.046
I was about to ask about
a seat on the plane.

36:13.046 --> 36:15.423
The residents, they need me
to get over myself,

36:15.423 --> 36:19.219
and apparently so do you,
so yes,

36:19.219 --> 36:22.430
I can put aside
my feelings about...

36:22.430 --> 36:25.600
Boston if there's
still room on that plane.

36:25.600 --> 36:27.686
<i>[tender music]</i>

36:27.686 --> 36:30.063
I think that can be arranged.

36:30.063 --> 36:31.690
- Good night.
- Good night.

36:31.690 --> 36:33.441
<i>Meredith: When a patient codes
or loses their airway,</i>

36:33.441 --> 36:35.902
<i>a doctor's first priority
is to get oxygen flowing.</i>

36:35.902 --> 36:38.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:38.488 --> 36:41.491
<i>We have a limited time
before damage sets in,</i>

36:41.491 --> 36:43.284
<i>so we spring into action...</i>

36:43.284 --> 36:45.078
Cheeseburger, no mayo,
extra pickles,

36:45.078 --> 36:46.871
- and a side of fries.
- I didn't order.

36:46.871 --> 36:48.248
- Did you want something else?
- No.

36:48.248 --> 36:50.625
I've just never been
a regular anywhere before.

36:50.625 --> 36:52.043
Yeah, well,
don't get used to it,

36:52.043 --> 36:54.921
because I just gave notice.

36:56.172 --> 36:57.799
You're coming back
to the hospital?

36:57.799 --> 36:59.718
- Yep.
- Ah.

36:59.718 --> 37:01.094
And there's something
I should tell you.

37:01.094 --> 37:02.762
Okay.

37:02.762 --> 37:06.182
Uh, as you know,
resident wellness

37:06.182 --> 37:08.727
- is important to me.
- Same.

37:08.727 --> 37:12.188
Uh, and I told Webber
that if I came back

37:12.188 --> 37:15.191
I wanted to be in a position
to help with that,

37:15.191 --> 37:17.068
you know, make sure
people don't burn out,

37:17.068 --> 37:21.406
that they have mentors,
and so Webber agreed

37:21.406 --> 37:23.658
to make me co-chief resident
with you.

37:23.658 --> 37:26.661
<i>[upbeat bluesy rock music]</i>

37:26.661 --> 37:30.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:30.206 --> 37:32.375
- [laughs]
- That's the best news ever.

37:32.375 --> 37:34.252
Okay.

37:34.252 --> 37:36.546
- I'm so glad you think that.
- Are you kidding?

37:36.546 --> 37:39.090
It's way too much work
for any one human to do,

37:39.090 --> 37:41.468
- plus it's you and me.
- I know.

37:41.468 --> 37:43.261
Were you surprised
when Webber agreed to it?

37:43.261 --> 37:44.971
Not nearly as much
as when he agreed

37:44.971 --> 37:46.598
to give me
eight weeks' vacation.

37:46.598 --> 37:48.933
- Eight weeks?
- Yeah.

37:48.933 --> 37:50.393
But don't worry, though.

37:50.393 --> 37:53.062
I'll give you plenty of notice
before I take it.

37:53.062 --> 37:55.648
Eight weeks.

37:55.648 --> 37:58.777
<i>Meredith: But in life,
time limits aren't as clear.</i>

37:58.777 --> 38:00.570
Do you want
to go to a wedding?

38:00.570 --> 38:02.489
Do they need a bartender?

38:02.489 --> 38:05.450
Okay, I have to say
something to you

38:05.450 --> 38:09.412
that is not very comfortable
for me to say...

38:09.412 --> 38:11.414
which is that I like you,
and I don't mean that

38:11.414 --> 38:12.874
as a boss or a friend.

38:12.874 --> 38:15.543
I like you like you,
and if you're not interested,

38:15.543 --> 38:16.711
that's okay.

38:16.711 --> 38:18.213
I will simply walk away
and possibly

38:18.213 --> 38:19.547
never step foot
in this bar again

38:19.547 --> 38:21.174
due to my previously
mentioned discomfort,

38:21.174 --> 38:24.719
but at least I asked...

38:24.719 --> 38:27.055
and if you are interested,

38:27.055 --> 38:28.723
my roommate Simone
is getting married,

38:28.723 --> 38:30.141
and I know
it's very last minute,

38:30.141 --> 38:31.226
but there will be
food and drinks,

38:31.226 --> 38:32.602
and I think dancing.

